title: Jared Goff rallies Cal past Washington State, 34-28
text:
Jared Goff rallies Cal past Washington State, 34-28 Originally published October 3, 2015 at 4:44 pm Washington State quarterback Luke Falk passes against California during the first half. (Ben Margot/AP) WSU played its most complete game of the year, but it wasn’t quite enough to knock off No. 24 California, and the Cougs fell, 34-28, to the Golden Bears in their Pac-12 Conference opener on Saturday afternoon. Cal, meanwhile, improved to 5-0 for the first time since 2007. By Stefanie Loh Seattle Times staff reporter 
BERKELEY, Calif. — Washington State played its most complete game of the year, but it wasn’t quite enough to knock off No. 24 California, and the Cougs fell, 34-28, to the Golden Bears in their Pac-12 Conference opener on Saturday afternoon. 
Cal, meanwhile, improved to 5-0 for the first time since 2007. The Golden Bears are also 2-0 in Pac-12 play. 
Quarterback Jared Goff passed for 390 yards and threw four touchdown passes to help Cal rally from what was a 21-7 deficit late in the first half. 
The game came alive in the third quarter, after Cal foiled a WSU fake punt attempt on fourth down and the Golden Bears’ Stefan McClure ran the fumble back for a 45-yard touchdown to cut WSU’s lead to 21-20. Most Read Stories
